title: For Sale:  Emerson SPECWAR knife
postcontent:
Up for sale is my Emerson/Neely Specwar knife, produced by Vaughn Neely at Timerline knives.  This one has the aluminum nitride coating (dark grey).  There is not a mark on this knife, it is as new.  These originally retailed for $300-$400, and they are no longer produced.  I am selling this to fund a new project. $200 OBO, cash only, no trades.
 Emerson-Neely Timberline SPECWAR 

Emerson's first collaboration with a knife manufacturer was with Timberline Knives in 1993 for his SPECWAR model. This model featured a one-side chisel-ground tanto blade almost 1/4 inch (6.35 mm) thick. Its handle was made from fiberglass-reinforced nylon molded around a near-full tang. Vaughn Neeley of Timberline designed the sheath. The knife was originally a custom piece designed for Naval Special Warfare Group One, and this factory version was soon entered in the trials for the Navy SEALs knife in 1995. Although it was not chosen by the Navy, the Emerson-Neely SPECWAR knife won Blade Magazine's 1995 American Made Knife of the Year Award at the magazine's Blade Show in Atlanta, Georgia, that same year and was displayed as an exhibit at the Metropolitan Museum of Modern Art in New York City from May 24 to August 15,1995

I have about 1 and a half FAL rifle parts kits to be sold as a lot. These parts have been sitting so long, I don't recall what specific model they were for. I can tell you one of the bolt carriers has the zigzag cuts in it I think making it a British L1 Al or an Indian Ishapore. You can also see the two installed selectors are the large type. But included is a smaller one as well. I think the installed selectors are Inch, but I think the extra one is a FAL type D. Regarding sights, the two installed are the flip up style, but the 3rd included one is fixed (not flip). The plastics suggest it is a UK model. It has the retractable cocking handle. The other one UE 57 A 2019 with AD on the opposite side.

The carrier with the zigzag cuts matches its bolt UE A 11972

I am pretty sure they are both Inch models when it is all said and done. As for the two BCG's, I would think they both are 7.62 NATO but I could be wrong.

postcontent:
Dan Wesson 2008 CBOB with factory night sights, box, papers, two mags - everything it came with new. Comes with factory stocks and the custom ivory stocks shown in the pictures, which I had made for it. I am the second owner. The first owner put less than 100 rounds through the gun. I've put less than 300 through it. It is phenomenally accurate. I personally shot 1" groups at 25 yards with this gun with a couple different loads. I carried it a bit, mostly in a Maxpedition go bag, but it saw a leather holster a few times. As such, it has some scattered light marks in the finish from carry, but is still a very nice gun. Most of the carry marks have to have the light hit them just right to see them. I took pictures of some of them to show them with lighting angles that highlight the marks, and can email those pics on request. I have owned Wilsons, Nighthawks, and a few other premium 1911s and this one is as nice as any of those at a fraction of the price. The trigger on this gun is stock and is amazing. The ivory looks much nicer in person than in the pics. It is creamy with nice grain and should age really nicely. I tried to capture that in the pics, but it is difficult to get the lighting just right for ivory, particularly newer ivory (bought these last year, so they haven't had much time to mellow).

I'll sell it one of two ways - with the ivories as shown for $1450 FIRM face to face in Hickory, NC or without them for $1300 FIRM face to face in Hickory, NC.  The ivories were custom made for this gun and fitted to it. They cost me over $250, so buying it with the ivories is the better of the two deals.  Not really interested in trades.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Arsenal SLR-96 AK-47 - Modified - Eotech and Magnifier Included
postcontent:
I have up for sale my Arsenal SLR-96, milled receiver AK 47, has been cerakoted.  This gun has been modified but unlike most "tactical" AK's listed for sale this has been done with all high quality modifications.  This is not a cheap AK with cheap ad-ons trying to be passed off as something it is not.

I will list below all modifications with their lowest available approximate retail price (that I could find with google).  I am the second owner of this gun and it has approximately 1500 rounds through it between both owners, (around 400 rounds since modifications completed). 

Selling as a package.  Only thing I will consider removing from the gun is the Eotech and magnifier and will take $700 off the price if you wish to purchase without the optics.

As a side note in order to remain 922r compliant you will need to use US made magazines or 2 of the 3 parts of your magazine must be US made or you must change out 2 additional compliance parts to US made if you wish to use imported magazines and remain 922r compliant.

Do your research on this gun and the modifications if interested and you will find that the SLR-96 is often argued as one of the highest quality AK's ever imported and that all modifications are top of the line.  Gun is in great shape.  

If you are in the market for a high end, top quality modified/"tactical" AK then this is the gun for you.  It is ready to go and you won't have to order the parts separately and pay for shipping and/or tax on most of them (which is not included in the prices listed below) and wait for weeks for the cerakote.

Price is firm.  I am not giving it away and will keep it if no serious interest.   I do not need the money and do not "need" to sell but if I sell I will use the money to fund other guns.  Otherwise, I will keep it as it is a great gun and fun to shoot.

SLR-96:  $1200
Not many SLR-96's for sale but compare with SA-93 and SLR-95 (SLR-96 is the rarest of the 3).

Cerakote finish:  $200

Mako Group/FAB Defense VFR-AK rail system with top rail:  $300
Top Rail screws to foregrip so it is one solid piece.  Gun can be field stripped without removing top rail or can be removed by unscrewing to access gas tube.  When optic is removed (quick release) iron sights can be used/seen down groove in middle of rail.
http://www.themakogroup.com/product_p/vfr-ak.htm
